"Grosse G., Schirrmeister L., Malthus T.J.","Application of Landsat-7 satellite data and a DEM for the quantification of thermokarst-affected terrain types in the periglacial Lena-Anabar coastal lowland",2006,"Polar Research","25","1",,"51","67",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-32044464048&partnerID=40&md5=cbb7e4203f69ced96ac27491908020cc","Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Postdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany; Institute of Geography, School of GeoSciences, University of Edinburgh, Drummond St., Edinburgh EH8 9XP, United Kingdom","Grosse, G., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Postdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany; Schirrmeister, L., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Postdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany; Malthus, T.J., Institute of Geography, School of GeoSciences, University of Edinburgh, Drummond St., Edinburgh EH8 9XP, United Kingdom","Extensive parts of Arctic permafrost-dominated lowlands were affected by large-scale permafrost degradation, mainly through Holocene thermokarst activity. The effect of thermokarst is nowadays observed in most periglacial lowlands of the Arctic. Since permafrost degradation is a consequence as well as a significant factor of global climate change, it is necessary to develop efficient methods for the quantification of its past and current magnitude. We developed a procedure for the quantification of periglacial lowland terrain types with a focus on degradation features and applied it to the Cape Mamontov Klyk area in the western Laptev Sea region. Our terrain classification approach was based on a combination of geospatial datasets, including a supervised maximum likelihood classification applied to Landsat-7 ETM+ data and digital elevation data. Thirteen final terrain surface classes were extracted and subsequently characterized in terms of relevance to thermokarst and degradation of ice-rich deposits. 78% of the investigated area was estimated to be affected by permafrost degradation. The overall classification accuracy was 79%. Thermokarst did not develop evenly on the coastal plain, as indicated by the increasingly dense coverage of thermokarst-related areas from south to north. This regionally focused procedure can be extended to other areas to provide the highly detailed periglacial terrain mapping capabilities currently lacking in global-scale permafrost datasets.",,"Landsat; periglacial environment; permafrost; thermokarst; Arctic Ocean; Laptev Sea",,,,,,"(2004) Impacts of a Warming Arctic: Arctic Climate Impact Assessment, , ACIA (Arctic Climate Impact Assessment) Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Are, F.E., The role of coastal retreat for sedimentation in the Laptev Sea (1999) Land-Ocean Systems in the Siberian Arctic: Dynamics and History, pp. 287-295. , H. Kassens et al. (eds.): Berlin: Springer-Verlag; Bartsch, A., Gude, M., Jonasson, C., Scherer, D., Identification of geomorphic process units in Kärkevagge, northern Sweden, by remote sensing and digital terrain analysis (2002) Geogr. Ann. Ser. A Phys. Geogr., 84, pp. 171-178; Black, R.F., Thaw depressions and thaw lakes - A review (1969) Biul. Peryglac., 19, pp. 131-150; Bolshiyanov, D., Makarov, A., Geomorphologic route along the Urasalakh River (2004) Russian-German Cooperation System Laptev Sea: The Expedition Lena-Anabar 2003, 489, pp. 67-74. , L. Schirrmeister et al. (eds.): Rep. Polar Mar. Res; Chavez, P.S., Image-based atmospheric corrections - Revisited and improved (1996) Photogramm. Eng. Remote Sens., 62, pp. 1025-1036; Czudek, T., Demek, J., Thermokarst in Siberia and its influence on the development of lowland relief (1970) Quat. Res., 1, pp. 103-120; Drozdov, D.S., Rivkin, F.M., Rachold, V., Anarjeva-Malkova, G.V., Ivanova, N.V., Chehina, I.V., Koreisha, M.M., Melnikov, E.S., Electronic atlas of the Russian Arctic coastal zone (2005) Geo-Var.